flowRoot.flowPara: A knowledge model can be then used to create a questionnaire that a Researcher or a whole team fills in for their project (or just to learn). Although the questionnaire can be very complex and contain hundreds of questions, the user won't be overwhelmed because only questions relevant for the specific case will be shown based on the previous answers. Integrations, references, and advices are also available to help with the answering. The questionnaire displays various indications including FAIR metrics. Answers can be then evaluated easily via various external integrated services within the Wizard that we call evaluators.

To support efficient, simple and smart work with data within research projects, an elaborate Data Management Plan is desirable. Wizard allows to generate such a plan from the answered questionnaire using a selected template and a format. Aside from human-redable PDF, DOCX, or HTML, having an machine-redable file in JSON is possible as well.Adopting FAIR Data principles is essential not just to satisfy requirements of funders, but to benefit your own research project as well.
- Data Management Plans (DMPs) are a key element of good data management and often required by funders and others (e.g. H2020 projects).

Knowledge models (KM) represent the data stewardship expertise in form of chapters, questions, possible answers, follow-ups, advices, references, integrations and so on. Data Stewards are the authors of this captured knowledge and can build it from scratch (new root KM) or just customize some existing KM by just simply adding, changing, or deleting some parts. This creates a forest-like hierarchical structure of the knowledge in the Wizard. Of course, KMs can be exported out, shared and imported again even in different instance of the Wizard.
